{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564860"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:19:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:19:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17157"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17157"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.08,0.01,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83219"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9847"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4520"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12080"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83219"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for antenatal care at eight weeks\u0027 gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She works as a childcare worker and is concerned about cytomegalovirus (CMV) exposure as she recently had a respiratory infection. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003Cbr /\u003ECMV IgG: Positive\u003Cbr /\u003ECMV IgM: Negative\u003Cbr /\u003ECMV IgG avidity: High (\u003E60%)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate interpretation of these results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Past CMV infection with immunity","Active CMV infection requiring antiviral treatment","Indeterminate results requiring repeat testing","Recent CMV infection requiring workplace modification","Primary CMV infection requiring amniocentesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s serology shows evidence of past CMV infection with positive IgG antibodies, negative IgM antibodies, and high IgG avidity. Understanding the interpretation of CMV serology is crucial in pregnancy, as the timing and type of infection determines the risk to the fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPast CMV infection with immunity\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated by positive IgG, negative IgM antibodies, and high IgG avidity. This pattern demonstrates previous exposure to CMV with developed immunity, which significantly reduces the risk of reinfection or reactivation. These women can safely continue working in childcare settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive CMV infection\u003C/strong\u003E would typically show both positive IgG and IgM antibodies, often with rising titres on serial testing and low avidity if primary infection. There is no evidence of active infection here, and therefore no indication for antiviral treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecent CMV infection\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated by positive IgM antibodies and low avidity IgG, which are not present in this case. There is no need for workplace modification as she has pre-existing immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary CMV infection\u003C/strong\u003E would be characterised by positive IgM antibodies with negative or weakly positive IgG antibodies and low avidity. This pattern would indicate recent infection and would warrant close monitoring and possible amniocentesis. This is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndeterminate results\u003C/strong\u003E typically show borderline or equivocal values requiring repeat testing. These results are clearly interpretable and do not require repetition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe greatest risk to the fetus occurs with primary maternal CMV infection during pregnancy, which carries a 30-40% risk of congenital infection. Reactivation or reinfection in women with pre-existing immunity carries a much lower risk (about 1-2%) of congenital infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Positive CMV IgG with negative IgM and high avidity indicates past infection and immunity, conferring protection against reinfection.","CMV IgG positive women can continue working in childcare settings during pregnancy.","Primary CMV infection during pregnancy poses the greatest risk to the fetus, while reactivation or reinfection carries minimal risk."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Management of perinatal infections: a consensus statement [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): RANZCOG; 2014 [cited 2024 Dec 10]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17157"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-02T16:36:39